            {
              "id": "017867c7-46ca-3695-9489-5cc0c185ef43",
              "name": "\"XSS Vulnerabilities from User-Controlled Data in Methods like `innerHTML`, `outerHTML`, or `document.write`\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn JavaScript, methods like `innerHTML`, `outerHTML`, or `document.write` can introduce XSS vulnerabilities if they are used to insert user-controlled data into the DOM. These methods interpret the inserted data as HTML, which can include potentially harmful scripts.\n\nIn the provided code example, the `innerHTML` method is used to insert user-controlled data (`t.minutes`) into the DOM, which can lead to an XSS vulnerability if `t.minutes` contains a malicious script.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate XSS vulnerabilities from user-controlled data in methods like `innerHTML`, `outerHTML`, or `document.write`, you should:\n\n- Use text content methods like `textContent` or `innerText` instead of `innerHTML` or `outerHTML` when inserting user-controlled data into the DOM. These methods do not interpret the inserted data as HTML, preventing potential scripts from being executed.\n- If you need to insert HTML into the DOM, use methods or libraries that automatically escape potentially harmful characters, such as the `innerText` property or jQuery's `text()` method.\n- Validate and sanitize user input to ensure it does not contain potentially harmful scripts.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe provided code example can be fixed by using the `textContent` method instead of `innerHTML`:\n\n```javascript\nminutesSpan.textContent = ('0' + t.minutes).slice(-2);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code example does not require any library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "0483fa46-049f-3a76-aa51-ff7fc74d42af",
              "name": "Detected Insecure Deserialization Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure deserialization is a vulnerability that occurs when untrusted data is deserialized by a program. This can lead to harmful consequences such as remote code execution, where an attacker can run arbitrary code on the victim's machine. In JavaScript, this vulnerability can occur when using functions like `eval()` or `Function()` to deserialize data.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid deserializing data from untrusted sources. If deserialization is necessary, use safe alternatives like `JSON.parse()`. This function only parses JSON-formatted data, and does not evaluate the data as code.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is an example of a vulnerable code snippet and how to fix it:\n\n**Vulnerable Code:**\n\n```javascript\nvar user = eval('(' + req.body.user + ')');\n```\n\n**Fixed Code:**\n\n```javascript\nvar user = JSON.parse(req.body.user);\n```\n\nIn the fixed code, `JSON.parse()` is used instead of `eval()`. This prevents the server from evaluating potentially harmful code contained in `req.body.user`.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017: A8-Insecure Deserialization](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A8_2017-Insecure_Deserialization)\n- [OWASP Cheat Sheet: Deserialization Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Deserialization_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-502: Deserialization of Untrusted Data](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/502.html)\n\nPlease note that all the links provided are active and accessible to anonymous users."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-502",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/502.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-502"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "083d75cb-7408-3c71-a56c-5cfab9eb3d62",
              "name": "XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data in HTML String",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) is a type of security vulnerability that enables attackers to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. A type of XSS vulnerability is when user-controlled data in a HTML string may result in XSS. This happens when an application includes untrusted data in a new HTML page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing HTML page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo prevent XSS vulnerabilities, it is important to:\n\n1. **Escape user input**: This means that you should make sure that any user input is properly escaped, so that it is treated as data rather than code.\n\n2. **Validate user input**: You should not trust user input and should validate it on the server side as well as on the client side.\n\n3. **Use HTTPOnly cookies**: This attribute can help to mitigate the impact of a potential XSS attack by preventing an attacker from accessing the session cookie via JavaScript.\n\n4. **Content Security Policy (CSP)**: Implementing CSP can effectively reduce XSS risks by declaring which dynamic resources are allowed to load.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple example of how to escape user input in JavaScript:\n\n```javascript\nvar userInput = \"<script>malicious code here</script>\";\nvar safeInput = escape(userInput);\n```\n\nIn this example, the `escape` function is used to make sure that the user input is treated as data rather than code.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
