                  "CWE-95"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "2149c3b7-7784-3091-8c24-5346399c05a3",
              "name": "\"XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data Anti-Pattern\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data Anti-Pattern is a common security vulnerability in JavaScript programming. It occurs when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, `$elem = $(link.hash);`, the application is directly using user-controlled data (`link.hash`) to select an element. This can lead to DOM-based XSS attacks if an attacker is able to control the `hash` part of the URL.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should:\n\n1. Avoid directly using user-controlled data to select elements.\n2. Always validate and sanitize user input.\n3. Use appropriate output encoding libraries to ensure that the output is safe to be included in HTML or JavaScript context.\n4. Use Content Security Policy (CSP) to reduce the severity of any XSS vulnerabilities.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly using `link.hash` to select an element, you should sanitize the hash before using it. Here is an example of how you can do this:\n\n```javascript\nvar hash = link.hash.replace(/^#/, \"\");\nif (/^[A-Za-z0-9]+$/.test(hash)) {\n    $elem = $(\"#\" + hash);\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, we first remove the `#` from the beginning of the hash, then we check if the hash only contains alphanumeric characters. If it does, we use it to select an element.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet requires jQuery to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP: DOM Based XSS](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/DOM_Based_XSS)\n- [OWASP: XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "2643bd0e-c6cd-3e27-8fab-ffa486d4234d",
              "name": "\"XSS Vulnerability Risk in User-Controlled Data within `hoursSpan.innerHTML`\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code snippet provided is vulnerable to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks. XSS is a type of injection security vulnerability where an attacker can inject malicious scripts into webpages viewed by other users. In this case, the vulnerability lies in the `hoursSpan.innerHTML` assignment. If the `t.hours` variable is user-controlled and not properly sanitized, an attacker could inject malicious scripts that would be executed when the `hoursSpan` element is rendered in the browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always sanitize user-controlled data before using it in your code. This can be done by using output encoding libraries when outputting user-controlled data. Also, you should use contextual output encoding. For example, HTML encoding when injecting user-controlled data into HTML.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using `innerHTML`, you can use `textContent` which does not parse HTML and therefore mitigates the risk of XSS attacks. Here is the fixed code:\n\n```javascript\nhoursSpan.textContent = ('0' + t.hours).slice(-2);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code snippet provided does not appear to have any library dependencies.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
