            {
              "id": "27877414-1d13-3ee9-8f4c-d204f3cb832a",
              "name": "Secure Regex Against User Input to Prevent ReDoS Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nRegular Expression Denial of Service (ReDoS) is a type of Denial of Service attack. It occurs when a regular expression (regex) is used to process user-supplied input and the regex is vulnerable to catastrophic backtracking. Catastrophic backtracking happens when a regex takes a very long time to evaluate certain inputs, potentially causing the application to become unresponsive or to crash.\n\nIn JavaScript, this vulnerability can be exploited if an attacker can control a part of the regular expression string. The attacker can provide a specially crafted input that causes the regex to take a long time to evaluate, effectively causing a denial of service.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, follow these general guidelines:\n\n1. Avoid using regular expressions if possible. If you must use them, make sure they are simple and not prone to catastrophic backtracking.\n2. Limit the size of the input that a regular expression can process.\n3. Use a timeout when evaluating a regular expression. If the regex takes too long to evaluate, abort the operation.\n4. Use tools to check your regular expressions for potential ReDoS vulnerabilities.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is an example of a vulnerable regex and how to fix it:\n\n```javascript\n// Vulnerable regex\nvar regex = /^([a-z])+$/;\n\n// Fixed regex\nvar regex = /^([a-z]{1,10})+$/;\n```\n\nIn the fixed regex, we limit the number of characters that can be matched to 10. This prevents an attacker from causing a ReDoS by supplying a very long string.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP ReDoS](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Regular_expression_Denial_of_Service_-_ReDoS)\n- [CWE-400: Uncontrolled Resource Consumption](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are active and accessible to anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-185",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/185.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-185"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "3678028d-d41b-3790-bbb5-2558d4199e2d",
              "name": "Redundant Variable Assignment Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn JavaScript, \"`d` is assigned twice; the first assignment is useless\" is a code smell that indicates a potential issue with variable assignment. This happens when a variable is assigned a value, and then reassigned a new value before the first value is used. The first assignment is therefore unnecessary and can lead to confusion and potential bugs.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this issue, developers should ensure that they only assign values to variables when necessary. If a variable is assigned a value that is never used before it is reassigned, this is a sign that the code could be cleaned up and potentially simplified. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is an example of this issue and how it can be fixed:\n\n```javascript\n// Problematic code\nlet d = 5;\nd = 10;\nconsole.log(d); // Outputs: 10\n\n// Fixed code\nlet d;\nd = 10;\nconsole.log(d); // Outputs: 10\n```\n\nIn the problematic code, `d` is assigned the value `5`, but this value is never used because `d` is immediately reassigned the value `10`. In the fixed code, `d` is only assigned once, eliminating the unnecessary assignment.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Code Review Guide](https://owasp.org/www-project-code-review-guide/)\n- [CWE-563: Assignment to Variable without Use ('Unused Variable')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/563.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are valid and active for anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-563",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/563.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-563"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "38e31393-9977-3319-b913-6cf4240a9659",
              "name": "XSS Vulnerability in User-Controlled HTML Data",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn the provided JavaScript code, the function is replacing spaces in a string with a regular expression. If the string is user-controlled and contains malicious scripts, it can lead to XSS attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo prevent XSS vulnerabilities, you should:\n\n- Use frameworks that automatically escape XSS by design, such as Ruby on Rails, React JS, etc.\n- Escape untrusted HTTP request data based on the context in the HTML output (body, attribute, JavaScript, CSS, or URL) will resolve Reflected and Stored XSS vulnerabilities.\n- Apply context-sensitive encoding when modifying the browser document on the client side acts against DOM XSS.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe provided code does not have any library dependencies. However, it is recommended to sanitize the user input before using it in the function. Here is a simple fix using the DOMPurify library:\n\n```javascript\nvar DOMPurify = require('dompurify');\nreturn '\\\\b' + DOMPurify.sanitize(str).replace(/ /g, '(?!-)(?!:)\\\\b|\\\\b()') + '\\:\\\\b';\n```\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "399bad74-b117-313e-960b-ad855c40eba0",
              "name": "Detected Insecure Deserialization Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure Deserialization is a vulnerability that occurs when untrusted data is deserialized by a program. Since serialized data can be altered and then deserialized, it can lead to malicious attacks such as code injection, denial of service, or privilege escalation.\n\nIn the provided JavaScript code, the `eval()` function is used, which is a common sink for Insecure Deserialization vulnerabilities. The `eval()` function evaluates a string as JavaScript code, which can lead to arbitrary code execution if the string is controlled by an attacker.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid using the `eval()` function whenever possible. If you must use it, ensure that the input is properly sanitized and validated to prevent arbitrary code execution. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using `eval()`, consider using safer alternatives such as `JSON.parse()` or `JSON.stringify()`. These functions are designed to safely parse and stringify JSON objects, respectively, and do not evaluate the input as code.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code does not appear to have any explicit library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Insecure Deserialization](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A8_2017-Insecure_Deserialization)\n- [CWE-502: Deserialization of Untrusted Data](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/502.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-502",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/502.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-502"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "4088c7e4-e50d-340e-8631-a604cc1ee8ec",
              "name": "Potential ReDoS vulnerability due to RegExp() being called with a `c` function argument in your application. Consider using hardcoded regexes, input validation, or a regex checking/sanitization library like 'recheck'.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe `RegExp()` function in JavaScript is used to create a regular expression object for matching text with a pattern. When this function is called with a `c` function argument, it can potentially allow an attacker to cause a Regular Expression Denial-of-Service (ReDoS) within your application. This is because the `RegExp()` function blocks the main thread, causing the application to hang or become unresponsive.\n\nReDoS is a form of Denial of Service (DoS) attack that exploits the fact that most Regular Expression implementations may reach extreme situations that cause them to work very slowly (exponentially related to input size). An attacker can then cause a program using a Regular Expression to enter these extreme situations and then hang for a very long time.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use hardcoded regular expressions instead of dynamically creating them with the `RegExp()` function. If your regular expression is run on user-controlled input, consider performing input validation to ensure that the input is safe before running the regular expression on it.\n\nYou can also use a regular expression checking/sanitization library such as [recheck](https://www.npmjs.com/package/recheck) to verify that the regular expression does not appear vulnerable to ReDoS.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using `RegExp()` with a `c` function argument, use a hardcoded regular expression. For example, instead of:\n\n```javascript\nvar re = new RegExp(userInput);\n```\n\nUse:\n\n```javascript\nvar re = /hardcoded_regex/;\n```\n\nAnd if you need to use user input in your regular expression, validate the input first:\n\n```javascript\nif (isValid(userInput)) {\n    var re = new RegExp(userInput);\n}\n```\n\n## Resources\n\n- [OWASP ReDoS](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Regular_expression_Denial_of_Service_-_ReDoS)\n- [CWE-400: Uncontrolled Resource Consumption](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-1333",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/1333.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-1333"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "42dbe0af-d9ac-3e40-b94f-0093ca71cb30",
              "name": "Redundant Variable Assignment",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn JavaScript, the vulnerability \"`c` is assigned twice; the first assignment is useless\" refers to a situation where a variable `c` is assigned a value twice in a row, without the first value being used. This is a code quality issue that can lead to confusion and potential bugs. It's not a security vulnerability per se, but it can contribute to them by making the code harder to understand and maintain.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this issue, developers should ensure that they only assign values to variables when necessary. If a variable is assigned a value that is never used, this is a sign that the code is not as clear and concise as it could be. Developers should strive to write code that is easy to understand and maintain, which includes avoiding unnecessary assignments.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is an example of this issue and how it can be fixed:\n\n```javascript\n// Vulnerable code\nlet c = 1;\nc = 2;\n\n// Fixed code\nlet c = 2;\n```\n\nIn the vulnerable code, `c` is assigned the value `1`, but this value is never used because `c` is immediately assigned the value `2`. In the fixed code, `c` is only assigned once.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Code Review Guide](https://owasp.org/www-project-code-review-guide/)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-563: Assignment to Variable without Use ('Unused Variable')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/563.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are active and accessible to anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-563",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/563.html"
