            {
              "id": "759d4aa4-7779-39aa-ae4a-1ff815c3b2a7",
              "name": "Prototype Pollution Vulnerability Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nPrototype pollution is a vulnerability that occurs when an attacker is able to manipulate the attributes of a JavaScript object prototype. When a prototype is polluted, all objects inheriting from that prototype will be affected, leading to potential security issues. This can be particularly problematic if the software relies on the existence or non-existence of certain attributes, or uses pre-defined attributes of the object prototype (such as `hasOwnProperty`, `toString` or `valueOf`).\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nThere are several ways to mitigate the risk of prototype pollution:\n\n- **Freezing the object prototype**: This can be done using `Object.freeze()`, which prevents new properties from being added to the object, existing properties from being removed, and prevents changing the enumerability, configurability, or writability of existing properties.\n\n- **Using an object without prototypes**: This can be achieved by using `Object.create(null)`, which creates a new object without a prototype.\n\n- **Blocking modifications of attributes that resolve to object prototype**: This can be done by using `Object.defineProperty()` to make an object's properties read-only.\n\n- **Using Map instead of object**: A Map is a simple key-value map and can iterate its elements in insertion order.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is an example of how you can freeze an object prototype to prevent prototype pollution:\n\n```javascript\nlet obj = { a: 1, b: 2 };\nObject.freeze(obj);\n```\n\nIn this example, the object `obj` is frozen, so it's not possible to add, remove, or change its properties.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-250: Execution with Unnecessary Privileges](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/250.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-915",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/915.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-915"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "760a12bd-9f13-3986-9be5-cd4be50f0709",
              "name": "Redundant Variable Assignment Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn JavaScript, \"`d` is assigned twice; the first assignment is useless\" is a code smell that indicates a potential issue with variable assignment. This happens when a variable is assigned a value, and then reassigned a new value before the first value is used. The first assignment is therefore unnecessary and can lead to confusion and potential bugs.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this issue, developers should ensure that they only assign values to variables when necessary. If a variable is assigned a value that is never used before it is reassigned, this is a sign that the code could be cleaned up and potentially simplified. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is an example of this issue and how it can be fixed:\n\n```javascript\n// Problematic code\nlet d = 5;\nd = 10;\nconsole.log(d); // Outputs: 10\n\n// Fixed code\nlet d;\nd = 10;\nconsole.log(d); // Outputs: 10\n```\n\nIn the problematic code, `d` is assigned the value `5`, but this value is never used because `d` is immediately reassigned the value `10`. In the fixed code, `d` is only assigned once, eliminating the unnecessary assignment.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Code Review Guide](https://owasp.org/www-project-code-review-guide/)\n- [CWE-563: Assignment to Variable without Use ('Unused Variable')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/563.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are valid and active for anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-563",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/563.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-563"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "7f51ca10-8f51-342f-862e-ca68e881e6d5",
              "name": "\"XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data Anti-Pattern\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data Anti-Pattern is a common security vulnerability in JavaScript programming. It occurs when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the vulnerability arises from the fact that the `container` variable is directly used to select an element without any sanitization or encoding. If the `container` variable is user-controlled and not properly sanitized, it can lead to an XSS attack.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate XSS vulnerabilities, it is recommended to:\n\n- Always validate user input: User input should always be validated before it is processed. This includes not only checking for script tags, but also HTML entities and other forms of obfuscation.\n- Use appropriate response headers: By setting the Content-Type and X-Content-Type-Options headers, you can prevent the browser from interpreting files as something else than declared by the content type.\n- Use Content Security Policy (CSP): CSP is an effective countermeasure to XSS attacks. It allows you to create a whitelist of sources of trusted content, and instructs the browser to only execute or render resources from those sources.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe code should be fixed to ensure that the `container` variable is properly sanitized before use. This can be done using the `text()` function in jQuery, which sets or returns the text content of selected elements. When setting the text content, any less than (<) and greater than (>) characters will be replaced with their HTML entity equivalents, effectively preventing any HTML injection.\n\n```javascript\nthis.$container = $('<div>').text(container);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the jQuery library to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "88716043-8dca-3de3-aab8-5497e5329f28",
              "name": "\"Logging Errors for Debugging and Security Monitoring in Empty Catch Block\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn JavaScript, an empty catch block suppresses errors silently. This means that when an error occurs within a try block, the catch block that follows it is supposed to handle the error. However, if the catch block is empty, the error is suppressed and not handled, which can lead to unexpected behavior in the program. This is a vulnerability because it can make debugging difficult and can also pose a security risk if the error is related to a security issue.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always handle errors in the catch block. This can be done by logging the error, which can help with debugging and security monitoring. It is also recommended to avoid suppressing errors silently, as this can make it difficult to identify and fix issues in the code.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is an example of how to fix this vulnerability in JavaScript:\n\n```javascript\ntry {\n  // code that may throw an error\n} catch (error) {\n  console.error(error); // log the error\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the catch block is not empty and it logs the error when it occurs. This allows for easier debugging and security monitoring.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP - Error Handling](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Error_Handling_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-390: Detection of Error Condition Without Action](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/390.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are valid and active for anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-390",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/390.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-390"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "891c5c58-8ad8-3d43-8f0d-15313d4986fa",
              "name": "Potential ReDoS Vulnerability Due to Use of `c` Function Argument in RegExp() Call: Consider Hardcoded Regexes, Input Validation, or Regex Checking/Sanitization Libraries for Mitigation",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe provided JavaScript code is vulnerable to a potential Regular Expression Denial of Service (ReDoS) attack due to the use of the `c` function argument in the `RegExp()` call. ReDoS is a type of Denial of Service attack that exploits the fact that most Regular Expression implementations may reach extreme situations that cause them to work very slowly (exponentially related to input size). An attacker can then cause a program using a Regular Expression to enter these extreme situations and then hang for a very long time.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, consider the following:\n\n1. **Hardcoded Regexes**: Instead of dynamically creating regular expressions, use hardcoded regular expressions whenever possible. This reduces the risk of creating inefficient or dangerous regular expressions from user input or other untrusted sources.\n\n2. **Input Validation**: Always validate user input before using it in a regular expression. This can prevent many types of attacks, including ReDoS.\n\n3. **Regex Checking/Sanitization Libraries**: Use libraries that can check or sanitize regular expressions to ensure they are not susceptible to ReDoS attacks. These libraries can analyze a regular expression and determine if it is potentially dangerous.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe specific vulnerability sink in the provided code is the `RegExp()` call with the `c` function argument. To fix this, you could replace the dynamic regular expression with a hardcoded one, or validate the `c` argument before using it in the `RegExp()` call.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code does not appear to have any library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP ReDoS](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Regular_expression_Denial_of_Service_-_ReDoS)\n- [CWE-400: Uncontrolled Resource Consumption](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-1333",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/1333.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
