            {
              "id": "98094ac4-88be-302d-8275-f0d32c8d9796",
              "name": "Potential ReDoS vulnerability due to RegExp() being called with a `b` function argument in your application.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe `RegExp()` function in JavaScript is used to create a regular expression object for matching text with a pattern. When this function is called with a `b` function argument, it can potentially allow an attacker to cause a Regular Expression Denial-of-Service (ReDoS) within your application. This is because the `RegExp()` function blocks the main thread, causing the application to hang or become unresponsive.\n\nReDoS is a form of Denial of Service (DoS) attack that exploits the fact that most Regular Expression implementations may reach extreme situations that cause them to work very slowly (exponentially related to input size). An attacker can then cause a program using a Regular Expression to enter these extreme situations and then hang for a very long time.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use hardcoded regular expressions instead of passing a function argument to `RegExp()`. If your regular expression is run on user-controlled input, consider performing input validation to ensure that the input is safe before running the regular expression on it. \n\nYou can also use a regular expression checking or sanitization library, such as [recheck](https://www.npmjs.com/package/recheck), to verify that the regular expression does not appear vulnerable to ReDoS.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using `RegExp()` with a function argument, use a hardcoded regular expression. For example, instead of:\n\n```javascript\nlet pattern = new RegExp(someFunction());\n```\n\nUse:\n\n```javascript\nlet pattern = /hardcoded_pattern/;\n```\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP ReDoS](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Regular_expression_Denial_of_Service_-_ReDoS)\n- [CWE-400: Uncontrolled Resource Consumption](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-1333",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/1333.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-1333"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "9e538bf6-b09e-37e5-a089-084a04b5e13e",
              "name": "XSS Vulnerability due to Dynamic Input in innerHTML",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `innerHTML` property is used to insert user-controlled input (`t.minutes`) into the HTML document. This is dangerous because it allows an attacker to inject arbitrary HTML or JavaScript code, leading to an XSS vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate XSS vulnerabilities, you should:\n\n- Use the principle of least privilege: Only allow necessary permissions for the user.\n- Validate input: Ensure that the input matches the expected format.\n- Escape output: Ensure that any output is properly escaped.\n- Use secure APIs: Use APIs, such as `innerText`, that automatically escape output.\n- Use Content Security Policy (CSP): This can help to mitigate the impact of any potential XSS vulnerabilities.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using `innerHTML`, use `textContent` or `innerText` which do not interpret the passed content as HTML, but instead insert it as raw text.\n\n```javascript\nminutesSpan.textContent = ('0' + t.minutes).slice(-2);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not appear to have any library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "a047b2c0-2284-3ed6-81f8-868ee014d29b",
              "name": "XSS Vulnerability in User-Controlled HTML Data",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn the provided JavaScript code, the function is replacing spaces in a string with a regular expression. If the string is user-controlled and contains malicious scripts, it can lead to XSS attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo prevent XSS vulnerabilities, you should:\n\n- Use frameworks that automatically escape XSS by design, such as Ruby on Rails, React JS, etc.\n- Escape untrusted HTTP request data based on the context in the HTML output (body, attribute, JavaScript, CSS, or URL) will resolve Reflected and Stored XSS vulnerabilities.\n- Apply context-sensitive encoding when modifying the browser document on the client side acts against DOM XSS.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe provided code does not have any library dependencies. However, it is recommended to sanitize the user input before using it in the function. Here is a simple fix using the DOMPurify library:\n\n```javascript\nvar DOMPurify = require('dompurify');\nreturn '\\\\b' + DOMPurify.sanitize(str).replace(/ /g, '(?!-)(?!:)\\\\b|\\\\b()') + '\\:\\\\b';\n```\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "aa0c1f36-d2a9-3a86-aca5-aefb69cee785",
              "name": "XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data in HTML String",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) is a type of security vulnerability that enables attackers to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. A type of XSS vulnerability is when user-controlled data in a HTML string may result in XSS. This happens when an application includes untrusted data in a new HTML page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing HTML page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo prevent XSS vulnerabilities, it is important to:\n\n1. **Escape user input**: This means that you should make sure that any user input is properly escaped, so that it is treated as data rather than code.\n\n2. **Validate user input**: You should not trust user input and should validate it on the server side as well as on the client side.\n\n3. **Use HTTPOnly cookies**: This attribute can help to mitigate the impact of a potential XSS attack by preventing an attacker from accessing the session cookie via JavaScript.\n\n4. **Content Security Policy (CSP)**: Implementing CSP can effectively reduce XSS risks by declaring which dynamic resources are allowed to load.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple example of how to escape user input in JavaScript:\n\n```javascript\nvar userInput = \"<script>malicious code here</script>\";\nvar safeInput = escape(userInput);\n```\n\nIn this example, the `escape` function is used to make sure that the user input is treated as data rather than code.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "aa882e08-2639-3aa8-b2c0-36a841fabd41",
              "name": "Exclusion of Unreadable Files from Scans Due to High False Positive Rate; Recommendation for Storage in CDN or Cloud Buckets",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe provided JavaScript code is an obfuscated script that uses the `eval()` function. The `eval()` function in JavaScript is a powerful feature that allows the execution of arbitrary JavaScript code represented as a string. However, it is also a common source of security vulnerabilities, as it can lead to arbitrary code execution if an attacker can control the input to `eval()`.\n\nThe vulnerability here is that the script may read files that are not intended to be read, leading to a high false positive rate. This can be a problem if the script is used in a security scanning context, as it may lead to unnecessary alerts and waste of resources.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nThe best way to mitigate this vulnerability is to avoid using `eval()` whenever possible. Instead, use safer alternatives such as `JSON.parse()` for parsing JSON data, or `Function` constructor for creating new functions dynamically.\n\nIf the use of `eval()` is unavoidable, make sure to sanitize and validate the input to `eval()`. Never pass user-controlled input to `eval()` without proper sanitization and validation.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe specific fix would depend on the exact functionality of the script. However, a general recommendation would be to replace the `eval()` function with a safer alternative. For example, if the script is used to parse JSON data, you could replace `eval()` with `JSON.parse()`.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code seems to be obfuscated and it's hard to determine the exact library dependencies without deobfuscating it. However, it seems to use the `XRegExp` library for regular expressions.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 - A1 Injection](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A1_2017-Injection)\n- [CWE-94: Improper Control of Generation of Code ('Code Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/94.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are subject to change and may not be accessible at a later date."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-94",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/94.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-94"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "ace59a22-3387-34e1-998a-2acbadd8360c",
              "name": "\"XSS Vulnerabilities from User-Controlled Data in 'MinutesSpan' Anti-Pattern\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"XSS Vulnerabilities from User-Controlled Data in 'MinutesSpan' Anti-Pattern\" vulnerability refers to a Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerability that occurs when user-controlled data is directly inserted into a web page without proper sanitization or validation. In this case, the vulnerability lies in the `minutesSpan.innerHTML` assignment, where `t.minutes` is user-controlled data.\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks are a type of injection, in which malicious scripts are injected into otherwise benign and trusted websites. XSS attacks occur when an attacker uses a web application to send malicious code, generally in the form of a browser side script, to a different end user.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always escape untrusted HTTP request data based on the context in the HTML output (HTML body, HTML attribute, JavaScript, CSS, or URL) will be consumed. When the data is used in HTML body content, use HTML entity encoding. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nA simple fix for this specific vulnerability would be to sanitize the `t.minutes` input before inserting it into the `minutesSpan` element. This can be done using the `textContent` property instead of `innerHTML`:\n\n```javascript\nminutesSpan.textContent = ('0' + t.minutes).slice(-2);\n```\n\nThe `textContent` property does not interpret the passed content as HTML, but instead inserts it as raw text, which prevents any potential script from being executed.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not appear to have any specific library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "b54c5f9b-b6c1-3616-8bf0-c7a46ef0d9e2",
              "name": "\"Exclusion of Unreadable Files from Scans Due to High False Positive Rates\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn JavaScript programming, a common vulnerability arises when files are minified, compressed, obfuscated, or otherwise made unreadable. While these practices can be a strong indicator of maliciousness, they also have a relatively higher false positive (FP) rate. This means that legitimate, non-malicious files can sometimes be flagged as malicious, leading to unnecessary alerts and potential disruption of normal operations. \n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is highly recommended to store such files in Content Delivery Networks (CDNs), cloud buckets, or similar storage solutions. This not only helps to reduce the risk of false positives but also helps to keep the codebase readable and maintainable. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nWhile there's no direct source code fix for this issue, as it's more about the organization of your code and files, you can follow these general steps:\n\n1. Avoid minifying, compressing, or obfuscating files unless absolutely necessary.\n2. If you must use these practices, store the files in a CDN or cloud bucket.\n3. Keep your codebase as readable as possible. This includes using clear variable names, adding comments to explain complex sections of code, and following other best practices for code readability.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE- obfuscation](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/1166.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are active and accessible to anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "b566b310-7dc6-3d08-acaf-d0aee935bfb6",
              "name": "XSS Vulnerability due to Dynamic Input in innerHTML",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `innerHTML` property is used to insert user-controlled input (`t.seconds`) into the HTML document. This is dangerous because it allows an attacker to inject arbitrary HTML or JavaScript code, leading to an XSS vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo prevent XSS vulnerabilities, you should:\n\n- Use the principle of least privilege: Only allow necessary permissions for the code to execute.\n- Validate input: Ensure that the input matches the expected format.\n- Escape output: Make sure that any user-supplied input is treated as display text and not executable script.\n- Use secure APIs: Some APIs provide automatic escaping to prevent XSS vulnerabilities.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using `innerHTML`, use `textContent` or `innerText` which do not interpret the passed content as HTML, but instead insert it as raw text.\n\n```javascript\nsecondsSpan.textContent = ('0' + t.seconds).slice(-2);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not appear to have any library dependencies.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Resources\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
