                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "b9a2b6cb-626f-3659-99ab-e4fce8d3f25b",
              "name": "Insecure Randomness Vulnerability in math/rand.Intn() for Security-Sensitive Uses",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure Randomness Vulnerability in `math/rand.Intn()` for Security-Sensitive Uses refers to the use of a pseudo-random number generator (PRNG) in a context requiring a cryptographically secure random number generator (CSPRNG). The `math/rand` package in Go uses a deterministic PRNG, which means that it can produce predictable values if the seed is known. This can lead to a variety of security vulnerabilities, such as predictable session identifiers, tokens, or other secret values.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, use a cryptographically secure random number generator instead of `math/rand`. The `crypto/rand` package in Go provides this functionality. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace `math/rand.Intn(500)` with a function that uses `crypto/rand` to generate a random integer. Here is an example:\n\n```go\npackage main\n\nimport (\n\t\"crypto/rand\"\n\t\"math/big\"\n)\n\nfunc secureRandomInt(max int64) (int64, error) {\n\tnBig, err := rand.Int(rand.Reader, big.NewInt(max))\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\treturn 0, err\n\t}\n\treturn nBig.Int64(), nil\n}\n```\n\nIn this function, `rand.Int(rand.Reader, big.NewInt(max))` generates a random `*big.Int` less than `max`, and `nBig.Int64()` converts it to an `int64`.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/rand`\n- `math/big`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Insecure Randomness](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Randomness)\n- [CWE-330: Use of Insufficiently Random Values](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/330.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-330",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/330.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-330"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c3bec28d-a4bc-365a-ab59-2ca152869ffd",
              "name": "\"Potential XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data in HTML String\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA potential Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerability can occur when user-controlled data is used in an HTML string. In the provided JavaScript code, the variable `href` is directly concatenated into an HTML string. If `href` contains malicious scripts, it can lead to an XSS attack when the HTML string is rendered in the browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to sanitize user-controlled data before using it in an HTML string. This can be done by using a library that provides HTML encoding functions to ensure that any potentially harmful scripts in the user-controlled data are treated as plain text and not executed.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n```javascript\nvar hrefSanitized = $(\"<div>\").text(href).html();\nvar $activeLink = this.$container.find(\"a[href$='\" + hrefSanitized + \"']\");\n```\n\nIn this fix, the user-controlled `href` data is sanitized by creating a new jQuery object and using the `.text()` method to set its text content to `href`. This effectively HTML encodes `href`. The `.html()` method is then used to retrieve the HTML-encoded `href`.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code example requires the jQuery library to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c84ad6b0-0820-3d80-b291-c79cf0c50f93",
              "name": "Potential SQL Injection Vulnerability Detected in String-Formatted Query",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code snippet provided is vulnerable to SQL Injection, a common security vulnerability that allows an attacker to manipulate SQL queries. This vulnerability occurs when user input is directly concatenated into a SQL query without proper sanitization or parameterization. In the provided Go code, the `category` variable is directly concatenated into the SQL query, making it possible for an attacker to inject malicious SQL code.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid directly concatenating user input into SQL queries. Instead, use parameterized queries or prepared statements. These techniques ensure that user input is always treated as literal data, not part of the SQL command.\n\n## Source Code Fix\n\nHere is a fixed version of the code using parameterized queries:\n\n```go\nquery := \"SELECT * FROM product WHERE category= ?\"\nrows, err := db.QueryContext(ctx, query, category)\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `database/sql`: This is a standard Go library for interacting with SQL databases.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "ca0b0b47-3c6c-35d1-a37f-16406ae36bc7",
              "name": "\"Vulnerability in Dynamic Execution with Eval and Function\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nDynamic execution using `eval()` and `Function()` in JavaScript is a vulnerability that arises when a developer uses these functions to execute code dynamically. These functions can execute any JavaScript code which makes them extremely powerful, but also dangerous if misused. If an attacker can influence the input to these functions, they can inject their own code, leading to a variety of attacks such as Cross-Site Scripting (XSS), Remote Code Execution (RCE), and others.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, the best practice is to avoid using `eval()` and `Function()` whenever possible. If dynamic script execution is necessary, consider safer alternatives such as `setTimeout()` and `setInterval()`, which can be used with string arguments. \n\nIf you must use `eval()` or `Function()`, make sure the input is properly sanitized and validated. This can be done using various techniques such as input validation, output encoding, and using appropriate HTTP headers to prevent XSS attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using `eval()` or `Function()`, consider using other JavaScript functions that allow you to run code dynamically. For example, instead of:\n\n```javascript\nvar code = \"alert('This is a test')\";\neval(code);\n```\n\nYou can use:\n\n```javascript\nsetTimeout(\"alert('This is a test')\", 0);\n```\n\nOr even better, avoid strings altogether:\n\n```javascript\nsetTimeout(function() {\n    alert('This is a test');\n}, 0);\n```\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n\n## CWE\n\n- [CWE-94: Improper Control of Generation of Code ('Code Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/94.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-94",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/94.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-94"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "caff959e-1835-30b5-b773-38e271e04e51",
              "name": "XSS Vulnerability due to Dynamic Input in innerHTML",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) is a type of security vulnerability that enables attackers to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. A web application is vulnerable to XSS if it uses unsanitized user input. XSS attacks occur when an attacker uses a web application to send malicious code, generally in the form of a browser side script, to a different end user.\n\nIn the context of JavaScript, using `innerHTML` can lead to XSS attacks if the input is not properly sanitized. This is because `innerHTML` interprets the passed string as HTML, including any scripts that the string might contain.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate XSS vulnerabilities due to dynamic input in `innerHTML`, you should always sanitize user input. This means that you should encode or escape the input so that it is safe to display in HTML context. \n\nIn addition, you should consider using `textContent` instead of `innerHTML` when inserting text from JavaScript into HTML. This is because `textContent` does not parse the passed content as HTML, but instead treats it as raw text.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of:\n\n```javascript\ndaysSpan.innerHTML = t.days;\n```\n\nYou should use:\n\n```javascript\ndaysSpan.textContent = t.days;\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not require any library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Resources\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP: DOM Based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "cdbb5194-101d-35cd-bda1-18d9dd63a9ff",
              "name": "\"Exclusion of Unreadable Files from Scans Due to High False Positive Rates\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn JavaScript programming, a common vulnerability arises when files are minified, compressed, obfuscated, or otherwise made unreadable. While these practices can be a strong indicator of maliciousness, they also have a relatively higher false positive (FP) rate. This means that legitimate, non-malicious files can sometimes be flagged as malicious, leading to unnecessary alerts and potential disruption of normal operations. \n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is highly recommended to store such files in Content Delivery Networks (CDNs), cloud buckets, or similar storage solutions. This not only helps to reduce the risk of false positives but also helps to keep the codebase readable and maintainable. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nWhile there's no direct source code fix for this issue, as it's more about the organization of your code and files, you can follow these general steps:\n\n1. Avoid minifying, compressing, or obfuscating files unless absolutely necessary.\n2. If you must use these practices, store the files in a CDN or cloud bucket.\n3. Keep your codebase as readable as possible. This includes using clear variable names, adding comments to explain complex sections of code, and following other best practices for code readability.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE- obfuscation](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/1166.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are active and accessible to anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "cea43233-ffa9-3447-88d9-1e3430c9c283",
              "name": "Potential Code Injection Vulnerability Detected through eval() Usage",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe provided JavaScript code uses the `eval()` function, which can lead to a potential code injection vulnerability. This is a serious security risk as it allows an attacker to execute arbitrary JavaScript code in the context of your website. This can lead to a variety of attacks such as Cross-Site Scripting (XSS), data theft, website defacement, and others.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid using `eval()` and its aliases (`setTimeout()`, `setInterval()`, and `Function()`). These functions can execute JavaScript code represented as strings, which can be manipulated by an attacker to inject malicious scripts. \n\nInstead, use safer alternatives to perform the same task. For example, if you need to parse JSON data, use `JSON.parse()` instead of `eval()`. If you need to call a function dynamically, use an object that maps strings to functions.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe provided code is obfuscated and it's hard to provide a specific fix without knowing its original purpose. However, the general recommendation is to remove the `eval()` function and replace it with safer alternatives.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code seems to be obfuscated and it's hard to determine the exact library dependencies. However, it seems to use the `SyntaxHighlighter` object, which suggests that it might depend on the SyntaxHighlighter library.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Resources\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017: Injection](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A1_2017-Injection)\n- [CWE-94: Improper Control of Generation of Code ('Code Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/94.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are subject to change and might become inactive over time. Always refer to the latest resources from OWASP and CWE for up-to-date information."
              },
